posts.title: Game Show App
posts.post:
This project involved creating a word guessing game. The application generates a random phrase in which players will use an onscreen keyboard to guess. The player may continue to choose letters. However, the game will end if either the player makes five incorrect attempts or correctly solves the phrase.


The player is greeted with a "Win" or "Lose" screen with the option to restart the game. The game restarts with a new phrase altogether.


Defining the project variables:


// Get the elements you’ ll need from your HTML


// Get the element with the ID of qwerty and save it to a variable.
const qwerty = document.querySelector('#qwerty'),
// Get the element with the ID of phrase and save it to a variable.
phrase = document.querySelector('#phrase');
// Create a missed variable, initialized to 0, that you’ ll use later to keep track of the number of guesses the player has missed
// (remember,if the player guesses wrong 5 times, they lose the game)
let missed = 0;
const startButton = document.querySelector('.btn__reset');


Starting the game: 


// Attach a event listener to the“ Start Game” button to hide the start screen overlay.
startButton.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    const startOverlay = event.target.parentNode,
    oldLetters = document.querySelector('letter')
    if(startOverlay.className === 'start' || startOverlay.className === 'win' || startOverlay.className === 'lose') {
        restart();
        startOverlay.style.display = 'none';
    }
});


Generating a random phrase:


getRandomPhraseAsArray = (array) => {
    const max = (Math.floor(array.length));
    const min = 0;
    let randomNum = Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min) + min);
    return array[randomNum];
}


Appending the phrase to the page:


addPhrasetoDisplay = (string) => {
    const phraseList = phrase.childNodes[0].nextElementSibling;
    for(let i = 0; i < string.length; i++) {
        let listItem = document.createElement('li'),
        listContent = document.createTextNode(string[i]);
        if(string[i] !== ' ') {
            listItem.className = 'letter';
        }
        listItem.appendChild(listContent);
        phraseList.appendChild(listItem);
    }
};

posts.title: Video Player
posts.post:
The video player project required matching the site layout to provided mock-ups for both mobile and medium-plus sized displays.


Configuring the viewport within the meta HTML tag handles this without much additional work.


File: index.html


<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">


The next step invoiced implementing a video player which uses captions. The video tag along with source and track tags achieve basic video playback and caption functionality.


          <div class="video__container">
              <video class="video__player" controls>
                  <source src="video/video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
                  <source src="video/video.ogg" type="video/ogg">
                  <track src="captions.vtt" kind="subtitles" srclang="en" label="English">
                  Your browser does not support the video tag
              </video>
          </div>


Two source tags ensure browser compatability for either the mp4 or ogg file formats. The track tag ensures the closed caption option is available to the user during video playback.

posts.title: Sample Survey Site
posts.post:
Website


This project is an extensive learning process. The design and implementation of various components required the usage of web and database languages such as HTML5, CSS3, PHP, and SQL. Usage of Adobe Dreamweaver allowed for quick implementation of a working HTML5 template with Bootstrap CSS.


HTML5 websites are compatible with nearly all desktop and mobile devices. Bootstrap itself is an external, pre-made cascading stylesheet.


Bootstrap serves two purposes. The first allows the team a wide range of site layout customizations with predefined div tags which the team can change or fine-tune. The second wraps the entire website with specific tags providing a dynamic user experience, regardless of screen resolution.


Outputs


The index page serves as the survey’s main portal. Visitors will quickly identify HGO’s mission. Most importantly, visitors will have immediate sight of three channels of communication with HGO: online surveys and contact information such as customer care’s phone number and office address. 


Ultimately, the index page’s objective involves visitors registering an account and providing immediate feedback. The links in the navigation bar and buttons below it are visible and the red color functions as an attention-grabber.


The overall design and theme of the website appears as close to the main site as possible, yet appear distinctive enough for users to identify the survey website. The site’s background image is from the upcoming Mozart production, The Abduction from the Seraglio.


Since the website uses Bootstrap CSS, the survey site will scale to the user’s device, rendering the need for multiple sites irrelevant. 


Inputs


The HGO user survey system is for receiving user feedback. Users are required to provide registration information and login before taking any surveys.


The index page features twelve links for navigation within and outside the survey site. External links, such as social contacts, direct users to other HGO related media.


Not all fields are required; however, the survey site uses HTML5 form verification to prevent users from registering without an email address and password.


Furthermore, this method of verification will prevent users from submitting blank text surveys and incomplete radio button questions.


Fields hosting sensitive information such as passwords are not visible, similar to standard password forms. 


Front-End Code


The front-end of the survey site is comprised of HTML5, CSS3, whereas PHP and SQL comprise of the back-end of the site.


Adobe Dreamweaver allowed for usage of a basic HTML5 template in tandem with Bootstrap for responsive layouts and design elements. By default, Dreamweaver with Bootstrap sources an external JavaScript file, but this site uses no JavaScript code. 


HTML


The reduction of HTML’s role in web design over the years is visible here. HTML tags for the survey site section off areas of the page into rows and columns, using custom <DIV> tags. 


Each tag has an identifier, which is customizable with the linked CSS file.


Throughout the site, entirely custom tags are identifiable with the names of basketball players for easy reference and lookup.


Each row and column’s size is adjustable based on the content the team wishes. Once again, the CSS file allows for the modification of a variety of cell and row elements from backgrounds, transparency levels, and end-user interaction. 


Bootstrap


Bootstrap provides the team with more than enough ways to customize the appearance of the website. It comes pre-loaded with custom buttons, such as those on the index page, along with the icons beneath it. However, its automatic scaling is why it is in virtually every modern website today.


This is possible by employing a grid system, taking advantage of HTML 3.2 and HTML4 elements such as <SPAN> and <DIV> tags, dividing the site into customizable chunks, which also scale with the screen’s resolution.

posts.title: Style Guide
posts.post:
This project required implementing CSS styles on a raw HTML document. A mock image of the completed project needed to match at two distinct breakpoints for mobile and desktop resolutions.


This project was completed entirely with Sass. Few HTML selectors are to be used for styling. Additionally, HTML classes use the block element modifier methodology for selection (BEM).


File Structure


D:.
├───css
│   ├───base
│   ├───components
│   └───utilities
├───images
└───scss
    ├───base
    ├───components
    └───utilities


The project's root directory has two folders for compiling SCSS files to CSS.


The Scss directory has subdirectories responsible for specific portions of the project's design, adhering to principles of scalable, modular architecture for CSS (SMACSS).


A Clean Slate


The base directory features rules to provide clean launching point for applying additional styles, as all browsers have varying default styles. In the case of this project, it's used to import a normalize.css file along with providing a border-box rule to all elements and a base line-height.


Filename: /scss/base/_base.scss


//the universal selector (*)
* {
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

//p elements
p {
    line-height: pem(24);
}


The utilities directory houses project essentials for developing DRY and syntactically awesome style-sheets.


Two Powerful Mixins: Adjustable Breakpoints and BEM Selections


Mapping variables with a key-value pair for loops is a powerful yet invaluable feature in all aspects of programming languages, and it's usage with Sass is no different.


Defining breakpoints for devices of varying widths is the foundation for responsive web design, and mobile-first approaches. Instead of repeating media queries for each rule and breakpoint, Sass allows me to define all of the project's breakpoints within one variable.


The variable then can be mapped to a specific mixin calling an if-else statement for display sizes.


Filename: /scss/utilities/_variables.scss


// ==========================================================================
// Breakpoints
// ==========================================================================

$breaks: (
    'sm': 479px,
    'med': 480px,
    'lg': 769px
);


Filename: /scss/components/mixins.scss


// ==========================================================================
// Media Queries
// ==========================================================================

@mixin mq($break) {
    $value: map-get($breaks, $break);
    $med: map-get($breaks, 'med');
    
    @if $value == null {
        @error "`#{$break}` is not a valid breakpoint name";
    }

    @else if $value < $med {
        @media(max-width: $value) {
            @content;
        }
    }

    @else {
        @media (min-width: $value) {
            @content;
}
    }
}

// ==========================================================================
// BEM Selectors
// ==========================================================================

@mixin e($element) {
    &__#{$element} {
        @content;
    }
}

@mixin m($modifier) {
    &--#{$modifier} {
        @content;
    }
}


Selecting elements by classname could not be any easier with the BEM mixin. A block is defined and it's subsequent elements and modifiers are easily nestable within the main block selector. This allows for clean, easily configurable, and DRY coding, which we'll see below with the grid system.


The Grid Layout


The utilities directory houses functions, variables, placeholders, and mixins for the project's grid layout, flexbox, margins, border-radius, and colors.


<div class="grid__row">
    <div class="grid__col--3">
      <a class="link" href="/">
          <img class="img--logo" alt="circles logo" src="images/logo.png">
        </a>
    </div>
    <div class="grid__col--9">
      <nav role="navigation">
        <ul class="nav">
          <li class="nav__item"><a href="#type">Typography</a></li>
          <li class="nav__item"><a href="#buttons">Buttons</a></li>
          <li class="nav__item"><a href="#forms">Form</a></li>
          <li class="nav__item"><a href="#images">Images</a></li>
          <li class="nav__item"><a href="#grid">Grid</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </div>


Filename: /scss/utilities/_variables.scss


// ==========================================================================
// Grid Config
// ==========================================================================

$grid--width: 1260;
$grid-row--width: percentage($number: 1);
$grid--columns: 12;
$grid--gutters: pem(5);
$grid-col--width: (
     '3': (3/$grid--columns), 
     '4': (4/$grid--columns),
     '5': (5/$grid--columns), 
     '6': (6/$grid--columns), 
     '7': (7/$grid--columns), 
     '8': (8/$grid--columns), 
     '12': (12/$grid--columns)
     );


The project's grid is defined with one row which is twelve columns wide. Each column's width is determined by a simple formula, column number divided by total columns. The power of CSS preprocessors allows for quick configuration of the grid by simply adjusting the variables above.


Filename: /scss/components/_grid.scss


.grid {
    @include e('row') {
        max-width: pixels($grid--width);
        margin-top: $margin--two;
        margin-bottom: $margin--two;

        @include mq('med') {
            display: block;
        }

        @include mq('lg') {
            @include flex($direction: row, $justify: space-between, $wrap: wrap);
        }
    }

    @include e('col') {
        @each $col, $width in $grid-col--width {
            @include m(#{$col}) {
                margin: 0 $margin--one $margin--two;
                flex: $width;
                &.centered {
                    @extend %centered--x;
                }
            }
            
        }
    }
}


The grid system uses both mixins in tandem for selecting the row, and columns within the row and applying the appropriate styles. The column selector is iterating through each key-value pair, ensuring the modifier column number matches its grid-column width.

posts.title: A Couple of Personality Traits that Happen to go a Long Way
posts.post:
Note: This post is an e-mail published on Aug 1, 2015

 

Tonight marks the waning hours of a fun month. Books were read, conferences were attended, seminars were watched, and I've learned a lot. Yes, it sounds boring to most people, but having the courage to go against popular opinion usually pays for itself in the long run. This sounds so cliché, but how many people actually do it? Plenty of things in life are easier said than done, and that is definitely one of them.

 

Think about some of the most successful people of this generation, last generation, or virtually in any era. Most if not all of them have encountered social obstacles on their way to accomplishing great moments in history. Steve Jobs, Albert Einstein, Martin Luther King, and Oprah, are just a handful of so many great people who have had it Apparently, everyone needs some stress in their lives to reach new heights. Think about it, one needs to lift weights to build muscle, jog to increase lung capacity, and on a smaller scale, become sick to strengthen the immune system.


Social stress builds one's ability to be resilient. Owning the ability to turn criticism into positive energy, or being able to inoculate oneself from naysayers (even the voice in our heads) is pure gold. The majority of millionaires surveyed ranked this trait as being crucial to their success according to Thomas Stanley's Millionaire Mind.


However, too much of anything is almost always bad, and too much stress from outside forces is most certainly lethal. With that said, I have found inspiration from the story of Park Yeon-mi, a woman who escaped North Korea to China, before transitioning to a free life in South Korea. Her life sounds like a movie script through and through. She was forced to learn three languages just in order to survive, on top of the harsh conditions she endured just to escape in the first place. She's the definition of a modern-day superhero by far.


Throughout grade school, bullies have come and go, whether they were fellow classmates or teachers, and yet, those were fortunate experiences. It is a bit weird to know public speaking is one of the greatest fears most Americans have. Some people are absolutely terrified of what others think of them, and it is unfortunate. It is a prison of the mind that I've definitely escaped in my earlier years, and I'm continuing to distance myself from. After a while, one person has heard every joke in the book, to the point of being able to poke fun at themselves every now and then. It can be a great icebreaker if used correctly.


Have you ever heard the phrase, it's not always about what you know, but who? If so, how many times? Most millionaires ranked the ability to make accurate judgments about people near the top of their list, during their days in school, according to Thomas Stanley's research. Warren Buffett keeps it short and simple,

posts.title: I Think I'll Be A Millionaire, What Do You Think?
posts.post:
Note: This is an e-mail published on Jun 29, 2015


Hey,

 

I hope everyone's making the most out of their summer and if, not, why? This was the same question I asked myself earlier this year. More specifically, why am I spending money on things that I think makes me happy, but really doesn't? This e-mail isn't me attempting to preach or evangelize anyone to live a stoic life or anything. I feel as if I'm on this crazy journey right now, on a path that hasn't been traveled a whole lot, and I guess this what ultimately started it all? Before all of the other e-mails?

 

It was back in January or February where I sat down at my desk and opened Microsoft Excel and plotted my finances, and from there, I didn't like anything that I saw. Things were pretty stark, if I'm living a lifestyle in which I'm spending more money that what I bring in, it doesn't matter what career I'll have. It doesn't matter if I'm earning $20 thousand a year or $100 thousand, I'll age into my 70's and 80's with no safety net to rely on. Even in shorter terms, what would happen if I end up with no one to rely on financially? What if I lost my job today? What if I got kicked out of school? How long would it take for me to bounce back?


I had some immediate answers, but I didn't like any of them. None of them tackled the root of the real issues at hand. The quick answer for me was to find more money, more sources of income.

 

Six months later, I'm grateful that I've spent much of my time reading financial books, participating in financial webinars, and just having a mentor. I've learned a lot, to the point where those same questions don't cause panic anymore. I'm smiling, and now I genuinely believe I'll be a millionaire within 20-25 years from now, and that's just from working a regular career. It's safe for me to assume that I've had at least 100 thousand dollars flow in and out of my bank account, or just given to me (and spent) prior to having an account to begin with. It's nice to see that the bleeding has stopped for good, and there's nowhere else to go but up.

 

So what's the plan? What's the desired end-game, besides a comfortable retirement?

 

Financial freedom.

 

This is by far the most important thing to me right now, above my career, relationships, etc. I've watched many people, most commonly the sports athlete and the TV stars. Even the common men and women at the workplace. The lesson is really simple; if I don't figure out money, I'll spend 80% of my days doing things I don't necessarily want to do just to make ends meet, and chasing some sort of mirage titled the "American Dream". Maximizing my income is nice, it's great. It's cool, but a ship with a hole in it will sink no matter how large it is. Even worse is a building a house on a cliff.

 

I learned that after reading The Millionaire Next Door, and Personal Finance For Dummies. My mind was so blown away, that I read them again in disbelief. Then I began reading the The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People, followed by The Intelligent Investor and A Few Lessons For Investors and Managers from Warren E. Buffett. These books, I hold close.

 


Here's the plan, and I apologize if this sounds incredibly simple:

 


  • Eliminate consumer debt (credit cards, loans) [Will be completed at the end of the year]
  • Build a savings account with at least 6 months of expenses covered, & make sure the interest on the savings is ABOVE the rate of inflation. [Will be completed by this time next year, if not earlier]
  • Begin paying off student loans and invest into an index fund (such as Vanguard, because index funds are absolutely AMAZING, ASTONISHING, and UNBELIEVABLE)

 

This sounds simple enough right? Well, I've been cutting expenses left and right for the last six months. I've sold my TV, my video games, my shoe collection, my iPad, my amazing smartphone. I challenged myself to see what I can live with and without, and I've realized I can live without all of that stuff. What makes me really unhappy is paying bills, being in debt to someone. It's a drowning feeling. Spending money on nice things provides a brief feeling of escape, but then it's right back to reality. I'm not a fan of the highs and lows of that lifestyle. I need something more constant, and this is it. A roof over my head, clothes on my back, food in the fridge, as long as these things are here, I'm satisfied, and with that satisfaction leaves a bit of extra change for investments.

 

My goal within the goal is to live off of half of my income and invest the difference. That might sound crazy to you, but I read something crazier; the average income of the world is somewhere between 18 and 20 thousand dollars. The average American salary is about 40 or 50 thousand dollars a year. Even the average American is already rich, and even worse, Americans are becoming increasingly unhappier. My take on this information? Wants and desires are insatiable, as I've learned from the story of a king and a beggar with his bottomless bowl. There will always be something else, bigger and better. Like the great Ice Cube told me, you better check yourself before you wreck yourself. I definitely got the hard part of life out of the way.

 

An analogy that I picked up from a millionaire that was interviewed in The Millionaire Next Door, is that money are like seeds, you can eat them, or plant them, and sow them later. I plan on having some amazing crops.

 

What motivates me? Everyone is capable of getting out of tight spots in life, however, as we grow older, the odds against us doing so become greater. Warren Buffett, one of the richest men on the planet believe that dragons are best to be avoided, even if you're capable of slaying them. You'll live a longer, and happier life. Better yet, prevention is better than the cure. I'll say amen to that.

 

Money planning aside, my summer has been great so far. I've been learning to speak Spanish day in and out for the past couple of months as well. Hopefully I'm fluent sometime next year at this rate. I'd love to speak at least 3 other languages besides English. It'll be a fraction of what this kid can do.

 

Thanks for your time guys, and I'll be back next month.

posts.title: A Few Excellent Books
posts.post:
Note: This is an e-mail published on May 26, 2015


Hey,


Every day, I'm reminded that I'm surrounded by great people. Whether I'm at a family barbecue, in class or at work, I see people working to improve themselves, their families, and workplace, while some just do it all without discriminating against any other aspect of their lives. It’s humbling to be in the presence of such people on a day-to-day basis.


A friend asked me over the weekend if I like to rely on others. After being stumped for a moment, I replied, “no.” If you don’t mind, I’d like to recant that statement. This life journey that I’m on, all of my experiences, I doubt it would be as enjoyable if it were not for each of you; from my parents, my siblings, cousins, aunts, and uncles, co-workers, classmates, friends, and so on. I wouldn't trade you for anything.


This is a good life; the journey, and everything that it entails.


It’s unfortunate that I haven't always had this perspective, but now is a better time than any. I've learned that now is the only time that exists, shaped by the lessons learned from yesterday. Philosophy aside, I've learned a lot since my last e-mail.


Final exams have concluded for some time now and this past weekend marked the end of the 2015 season at the Houston Grand Opera. I've read five books, watched one movie, and failed at a personal budgetary goal (which I’ll share next month). However, this month has been a fun ride.

How did my 2015 spring semester end at UHD?


  • Statistics D
  • Marketing C
  • Business Law B
  • Management B


An overall disconnection between preparation and execution is the hallmark of this past semester. I’d like to believe I was just as close to an A in each of the classes that I have a B in and close to a B in the other courses. I failed my final exam for Marketing (48/100) and received a D in my statistics final exam.


There’s a brief story (or excuse) for each of the results, and I’ll share both, but not for one moment am I asking for some sort of pity or empathy, because I do believe the moral of both stories are the same.


I simply had to use the restroom during the statistics exam. The professor stated that I could not, and reprimanded me for simply asking the question, further stating that its explicitly mentioned in the syllabus that no student can leave the classroom for any reason during the final exam (I just checked, and it’s not true).


I shared this story with a few friends. Some stated they would have just peed on themselves right then and there. Others said the professor was just a jerk. For a moment, I seriously debated the former, and the latter is just simply irrelevant. It is what it is. I chose not to use the bathroom on myself and completed as much as I could without exploding on myself.


Each of my marketing exams was open-book, including the final exam. However, for whatever reason, the e-book was not allowed for the final. The e-book and my notes were all that I had.

The moral of it all is that I reap what I sow. I did not invest enough time understanding the material or finding classmates to study with. I was more reactive than proactive this past semester, and this is the result of that.


It was the complete opposite of how I studied for my other courses last fall. Instead of making sure I understood, I relied on the book to carry me along. Well, that won’t happen again. The same could be said for my statistics course. I should be able to spend much less time per question and should have at least made it out of there with a C if not higher (given the circumstances).


What I do find somewhat impressive, is that in the midst of studying for exams and virtually working full-time, is that I found the time to read. Here’s a list of the books that I've read this month:


  • The ONE Thing (Gary W. Keller & Jay Papasan)
  • A New Earth (Eckhart Tolle)
  • The Untethered Soul (Michael A. Singer)
  • The Lessons of History (Will & Ariel Durant)
  • Influence (Robert B. Cialdini)


There’s so much I would like to share with you all from each of these books, and I do believe I will create a blog or some website offering reviews of each. In the meantime, here’s a brief take from what I've read.


A New Earth and The Untethered Soul are what I consider to be spiritual awakening books. What is the ego of a man? Do you have an inner voice in your mind suggesting what you want, and what you need? Eckhart Tolle and Michael Singer describe the forces within our mind that influences our decisions. It may cause someone to rationalize that they aren't being loved, that they do not have enough money, time, and other tangible or intangible things.


When we act upon the desires of the ego, or the voices in our heads, we hasten our demise, to live an unfulfilled life. The ego of a man usually does not live in the present moment (as in right now). It is continuously influenced by matters of the past and various future goals and outcomes that may or may not ever come to fruition. The key to solving this problem is by identifying the voice, or the ego and give it space.


To not allow it to influence your life. Tolle describes this phenomenon as being present, living in the here, the now (not to be confused with living a YOLO-type of lifestyle).


Influence of Robert Cialdini is a mind-blowing book. It describes the essence of marketing, how advertising in today’s age has such a powerful effect on us. However, that’s just the tip of the iceberg.


Everyday people, such as you and I can use the power of influence to get people to do things they would not normally do on their own. Part of it is similar to the martial art of Jujitsu, in which the user wields a relatively small amount of force to take on a much larger opponent. The opponent, in this case, is the ego of another man.


Cool (or not so cool) story: So, for one of our performances here at HGO, we were in dire need of filling up the floor seats for the performance. In this case, we tend to offer discounts to students and seniors. Someone called in asking for fifteen dollar tickets.


He was looking for a deal. A great one, because the starting price is sixty-five dollars. Instead of flat-out rejecting him and hanging up, I said, “I wouldn't be able to offer you tickets at that price, but I can cut you a deal. We have some seats that are priced at $240 a ticket, but since you’re looking to save money, I’ll sell them to you for $80 a piece”. The man was excited and ended up purchasing tickets later that evening at the box-office.


That’s just one of several simple things that have gradually mind-blowing consequences. The craziest story has to be how the Chinese were able to convince American POW’s to believe in communism out of their own free will. Inception is real folks, and I'm not talking about having multiple dreams within a dream, but proper persuasion can make a person buy into an idea, and that idea will grow legs of its own.


The Lessons of History is a book I won't go into detail, simply for the fact that many of the book’s subjects (if not all of them) are highly controversial. However, the Durants take a look back at their findings throughout history and paint a picture. This picture is often grim, as it appears to be the cold, hard truth about human nature.


The biggest takeaway from this book is on the subject of education. The authors suggest that there are more opportunities than ever for the man to educate himself in this era, and education by far is the fastest way towards freedom in a world where every man is not equal. They state,

 

“Utopias of equality are biologically doomed, and the best that the amiable philosopher can hope for is an approximate equality of legal justice and educational opportunity. A society in which all potential abilities are allowed to develop, and function will have a survival advantage in the competition of groups”.


“The only real revolution is in the enlightenment of the mind and the improvement of character, the only real emancipation is individual, and the only real revolutionaries are philosophers and saints”.


Hey, I'm no saint, and definitely, do not consider myself to be a philosopher. Every day, I realize I am ignorant of a lot of things, and I'm just trying to chip away at it with what feels like toy hammer.

Last, but not least, The ONE Thing is a book that will help contribute to a strong foundation for anyone to build a good life on.


Each of these books is, but regarding plain-speak, no fancy words, just hard evidence, this is the book. Gary Keller and Jay Papasan put together what it takes to find a purposeful life in its simplest form.


No matter what a person wants to be successful at, this is the book. I'm going to copy and paste a piece that I wrote about the book to my Business Law professor, as I was evaluating my dismal semester:


“Managing oneself is imperative. Gary Keller, the author of “The ONE Thing: The Surprisingly Simple Truth behind Extraordinary Results,” states, “Think of willpower like the power bar on your cell phone.” … “Willpower has a limited battery life but can be recharged with some downtime. It’s a limited but renewable resource.”


In other words, the consequences of procrastination are given an easier image to visualize. Too many days were used inefficiently, studying late nights before class days and exams, while willpower was running low.


Studying late also cuts into the downtime needed to re-charge willpower to full capacity. Instead of being capable of operating until six or seven in the evening, a partial charge may reduce that by three or four hours.”


I could go on and on about this book and many more, and maybe I will, and these e-mails could be cut down much shorter in length. In conclusion, again I'd like to thank you all; mostly for your time.


Hopefully, the next email won’t be as long, and I’ll try to save the book reviews for another medium. I hope everyone enjoyed their holiday weekends and were able to stay dry given the weather here in Houston. In the meantime, it’s back to more education, backed by a renewed dedication.

posts.title: The Adjacent Possible
posts.post:
I've read a lot of books between seven months ago and today. Discovering new ideas or filling in gaps in a grand scheme is the fun and exciting part of reading them. Life was once moving at a snail's pace, and now, it feels all too short.


I have noticed I am lagging behind when I consider my end goal, yet playing catch-up is fun. I am climbing upon what others have constructed from their early age until now and thoroughly enjoying the view along the way. That is until I reach the adjacent possible. That is if I reach the adjacent possible.


The blueprint for success in many fields has been laid out for me; how to finish college, how to code a website; how to read/write; how to fix a computer, how to land a successful career, and ultimately how to become a millionaire.


However, the blueprints are not explicit. There is no literal how-to guide to achieving great success. Why? There are many reasons. However, most can be traced back to what a person does when they encounter the adjacent possible.


What is the adjacent possible? Steven Johnson of the New York Times states,


The adjacent possible is a kind of shadow future, hovering on the edges of the present state of things, a map of all the ways in which the present can reinvent itself.
The strange and beautiful truth about the adjacent possible is that its boundaries grow as you explore them.

Cal Newport, author of So Good They Can't Ignore You, shares his thoughts on the adjacent possible,


I was pondering Johnson’s theory of innovation: A good career mission is similar to a scientific breakthrough—it’s an innovation waiting to be discovered in the adjacent possible of your field. If you want to identify a mission for your working life, therefore, you must first get to the cutting edge—the only place where these missions become visible.

I had the hardest time wrapping my head around trying to understand the how's and why's around this term. I forgot about it and moved on after a few days. It was not until I picked up Arnold Schwarzenegger's autobiography, Total Recall, in which I saw a man reach and surpass the adjacent possible on multiple occasions, before the age of 30. The way in which he goes about retelling his life makes the task seem so natural and effortless. His book began connecting the dots, how to develop skills and leverage them to achieve small goals, which build momentum to a much larger goal. I'll try to summarize the layout of his goals and how things played out:


  • A young Arnold was mesmerized by the appeal of the United States. He believed that America was IT for him, though he was not exactly sure as to why.
  • As a teen, he began bodybuilding around the age of fifteen.
  • He began competing in European contests
  • By default, he was enlisted in the Austrian armed forces.
  • Arnold learned how to command a tank, and lay bricks (and gained a lot of experience due to crashing the tank into walls by accident).
  • His pleaded with his superiors that bodybuilding was his passion, and wanted to be discharged from the military.
  • He moved to Germany, made new friends and learned how to promote a local gym he worked for.
  • At age 19, Arnold won his first Mr. Universe event in London.
  • Arnold would continue to win until he was recognized by talents in the United States


I could go on and on, and it just gets better and better. After winding up here in the U.S., Arnold continued to train and win events. During this time, he would spend his measly income on English courses. More doors began to open for him, he took business courses, learned real-estate, and had several businesses running concurrently, and this was before he was an actor. Also, this was before he was 30 years old.


Also, this is within the first 200 pages of an 800+ page book! The first three chapters would have made a great book by itself, but I digress. Arnold was a trailblazer. His initial goal was to end up in America. He eventually saw the sport of bodybuilding as a way of accomplishing that goal, and he knocked it out of the park.


Once he was here, he felt as if the sport wasn't popular enough, and figured he would take promoting the sport into his own hands. Throughout that adventure, he took up acting, and the rest was history.


The adjacent possible is an obstacle, and the only way past it is innovation. Arnold has innovated himself to the point of he was a man who wore many hats. He was a salesman, bricklayer, actor, and landlord, and it started with one thing.


We'll ignore the fact that he was elected governor of California. Along the way, he noted several avenues in which he could have parked and settled into a fine career, but he continued to push past this obstacle.


His story is highly motivating and serves as a reminder that I have a lot of work to do in my respective field. Thankfully, the ground for me has been paved by many other trailblazers in the field of information technology and web design. All I have to do is stay on that path, and hopefully, I will have enough experience to innovate my way through and leave a mark on the world.

posts.title: Optimizing Yu-Gi-Oh Decks With Linear Programming (Kozmo)
posts.post:
Click Here to View YouTube Explanation/Tutorial


Brief How-To (For Now):

First things first: Enable Solver in Microsoft Excel.

In addition, enable Macros for Microsoft Excel.

Finally, enable the Solver reference for Excel VBA.


Do this by pressing ALT + F11

Followed by clicking Tools > References > Solver




Card Limit: How many cards you are legally allowed to play in the format, or that you don't want in your deck.


Cost to Activate: What cards you lose to gain a desired summon or effect.


Advantage: Cards gained by either drawing, destroying opponent's cards, or by other means.

Net: The difference between cards lost and cards gained.


Priority: How important is this card to the opening hand? On a scale of one to three, it's either "Lock", "Yes", or "Meh".


Brick: Can this card clog your opening hand, being unplayable without a combo piece? The answer is either "Yes" or "Kinda", followed by anything else. I define normal summonable monsters, and or hard once per turn cards, as "Kinda" bricky.


Disrupt?: Can the card disrupt the opponent's plays during their turn?

The optimizer requires a minimum of 10 cards to be disruptive in some capacity.


Download:

Deck Optimizer (latest version)

posts.title: Yu-Gi-Oh! Deck Optimizer ver. 0.0.9 and Deck Optimizer Pro
posts.post:
Warning: These files contain VBA script. Microsoft Office disables this by default for security purposes. So do not download these files from anywhere other than here. Anyone bright and malicious can easily alter these files and make them perform in ways I have not intended. Trust the original source and the original source only.


10/17/16 Update:

  • Fix to improve 60 card-limit decks and combos.
  • Fix to Pro version probability rating system (a double subtraction existed in one formula).

Download (Card Database is up-to-date as of the OCG release of Raging Tempest):

Deck Optimizer ver. 0.0.9


Hey,


It has been quite a while since I have provided any updates on YouTube and the blog here. Hopefully, those who are using the previous version of the tool have had some moderate success with it. However, I was not completely satisfied with it. Why?


Combos. I wanted combos with precision. The old tool required a good amount of hand-holding to create combo decks that are consistent.


This update will now help duelists create decks featuring a variety of combos while maintaining resources with efficiency. The implementation of combo constraints will finally allow users to fine tune matching pendulum scales, ritual cards, synchro plays and so on.

Let's take a look.


Additional columns have been created to provide room for single card plays, as well as multi-card combos (up-to four cards). All the user needs to do here is type in "Yes" (without quotations) in each cell corresponding to the card name. For example, let's take a look at the Red-Eyes Archetype.


Here we can see that I have selected a few one card plays such as Red-Eyes Fusion (and Insight, since it searches out Red-Eyes Fusion) and The Black Stone of Legend. However, we see a two card combination as well.


I want to ensure that when I open with Pre-Preparation of Rites, that I have the best opportunity available to ritual summon a monster on the same turn if I choose so. In order to achieve this combo, "Yes" is in place in the cell corresponding to Pre-Preparation of Rites, as well as appropriate tribute fodder.


In addition, we see there is a "Prerequisite" column. This is another column similar to the "Priority" column in the previous tool. However, the "Prerequisite" column is much more of a hard lock to ensure I have a specific number of copies of whichever cards I want.


Type "Yes" in the appropriate cell within the "Prerequisite" column to use it.

Let us scroll down to the near bottom of the tool.



Here is where I tell the tool how many cards I want in each combo.


Comparing the images above to this one illustrates that I want 3 copies of Red-Eyes Fusion and Red-Eyes Insight for a total of six single card plays for my opening turn.


In addition, I want 3 copies of Pre-Preparation of Rites and a total of 12 cards useable as tribute fodder for Paladin of Dark Dragon, including itself.


Before I run the tool, lets check the basic tools.



If you have not noticed, or are new to using this tool, yellow cells means it requires user input. Everything else is hands-off (unless you like a malfunctioning tool).


Here, a user can modify the Deck Size, Opening Hand Size (the Opening Hand Consistency will adjust), how many "Brick" cards in the deck, along with other types of cards.


The "Prerequisites" cell determines how many cards within the "Prerequisites" column will be used within the deck. The tool will generate the desired quantity of cards, however the user may have to adjust the actual cards used as they see fit.


All fields except for the Deck, Opening Hand Size, Net, Brick, and Priority Emphasis are optional.


Priority Emphasis is a new field compared to the old optimizer tool. Adjust this number to increase or decrease sensitivity of the "Priority" column. Any number greater than or equal to 40 effectively turns this feature off. 12-15 is very sensitive, and 20 is moderate.


Use this feature if you prefer not to use any combos for the moment being.


However, if you want to use combos with maximum precision, turn it off. I do.


The formula for consistency has also been changed. The previous optimizer calculates the probability of a user opening with hands that have no less than 3 brick cards.


Now, it is 4 card hands, which falls in line with the option of creating 4 card combos.

With great power comes great responsibility.



If you see this pop-up when running the tool, check your combos and check the basic tools. It is possible to simply run out of space within a deck. I have learned that with the creation of this iteration of the tool.


Sometimes I may ask for 6 cards I only have 3 playable cards available within a specific piece of a combo. Other times, the net card advantage I desire is too high.


Or I have learned that I cannot add any more traps to the deck without making some sacrifices elsewhere.


This may be a trial-and-error process, depending on your level of creativity.


Ok, I have fully covered the gist of the Deck Optimizer Tool's most recent update.


Now, I've added a few features that should be immensely useful for competitive players.



Probability and statistics made easy. Here's a screenshot of what I used to create an ABC Dragon Buster deck with. The opening hand success rate is absurd with a probability of 0.77.


In other words, I have a 77 percent chance of having either a rank 4 play, ABC Dragon Buster, and or Cyber Dragon Infinity on the first turn. If not, there's a very good chance that the hand is more than playable, given the 99 percent opening hand consistency.


I believe deck building is what separates good and elite duelists. Every competitive deck should have combos sitting around an opening hand success rate no less than 66 percent, and this tool will ensure that level of success.


Why is 66 percent the magic number? 66 percent is the equivalent of 2 out of 3. In other words, desired card combinations are likely to be achieved twice in a match.


The display of probabilities is vital, as it will also allow the user to determine how much free space he or she has in the deck for side-deck options, allowing for powerful counter-plays without disrupting the probabilities of desired opening hand combinations.


For those not proficient with probabilities, may have noticed that 68% + 25% + 19% equals 112%. What gives?


Simply put, you would not be wrong, but this information serves us no good. These card combinations can overlap one another in one opening hand. Therefore, the final probability of 0.77 is an outcome that discards overlapping combinations, as a hand with multiple desired combos does not carry over to the next duel. We just want to know how often we can draw into at least one of our desired plays.


Lastly, we have the "Archetype Lookup" feature. If you want to spend as little time as possible in this tool, and more time dueling, this feature is here to assist. Double click the green cell or simply begin typing the name of an archetype.



You will then be greeted by a list of common cards associated with the respective archetype.



Simply select the cards you want, copy and paste into the cells above and get straight to work.



Lastly, the Pro version is a one time purchase. Any new features will be available to you, provided you can show proof of purchase.


Any card database updates will be available to everyone.


Happy deck building.

posts.title: Lightbox Photo Gallery
posts.post:
The lightbox project features the usage of a couple of JavaScript technologies such as jQuery and ECMAScript 6 to display an interactive photo gallery similar to what major sites use such as Facebook and Twitter.


The search bar on the page uses a combination of functions to filter out images based on each of the photos names.


Also, the jQuery plugin, Lightbox is used to provide an interactive photo gallery. Lastly, the CSS implemented ensures a responsive design across all display sizes.


A validation check via w3.org ensured both the HTML and CSS documents are error-free.


Mobile-First Design

Included breakpoints for medium and large displays.


@media (min-width: 768px) { 

... 

}; 
@media (min-width: 1024px) {

 ...

 };


Content Filtering with JavaScript

A search function will execute for each key press. The function initiates by selecting all available images with the 'image-links' class name and stores the results within the 'imageArray' variable as an array.


//1. The search box at the top of the page shall filter photos based on the caption.

const searchBox = document.querySelector(".search-box");

//2. The photos should filter in real-time as you type

searchBox.addEventListener("keyup", () => {
  const searchInput = searchBox.value.toLowerCase(),
        imageArray = document.querySelectorAll(".image-links");
  //2a. Only the results shall display.
   for (i = 0; i < imageArray.length; i++) {
      const dataTitles = imageArray[i].getAttribute("data-title");
      if(dataTitles.toLowerCase().indexOf(searchInput) > -1) {
          imageArray[i].style.display = "";
      } else {
          imageArray[i].style.display = "none";
         }
    }
});


A for loop iterates through each array item using the typed inputs as a parameter, comparing the inputs with each array item.


All non-matching results have its display set to none to remove it from the available list of images.

posts.title: React Flickr Gallery
posts.post:
This project required me to create a single page application capable of querying Flickr's image database via their API.


Additionally, the React Flickr Gallery app became much easier to develop using Create React App, allowing me to focus on the content and functionality of the application without configuring anything.


Components

Creating components to match the mock images was the first order of business. Most of the components are stateless functional components, only to interact with whichever props are passed to them.


Application Map

The app employs several components. However, the 'App' component ensures all routes or parameters corresponding to a page. A not-found page will render if no applicable results are found either via the search bar or by address parameter.


const App = () =>{

return (
<BrowserRouter>
<div className="container">
<Switch>
<Route exact path="/" render={() => (<Search api={apiKey} />)}/>
<Route path="/cats" render={() => (<Cats api={apiKey} />)} />
<Route path="/computers" render={() => (<Computers api={apiKey} />)} />
<Route path="/dogs" render={() => (<Dogs api={apiKey} />)} />
<Route component={NotFound} />
</Switch>
</div>
</BrowserRouter>
);
}


Search Queries

The Flickr API is used in either one or two ways. The end user types in a parameter within the address bar for the site or the user enters a query into the search bar.


componentDidMount() {
if (this.props.query !== "") {
axios.get(`https://api.flickr.com/services/rest/?method=flickr.photos.search
&api_key=${this.props.api}
&tags=${this.props.query}
&per_page=16
&format=json&nojsoncallback=1`)
.then(response => {
this.setState({
keyword: this.props.query,
photos: response.data.photos.photo,
loading: false
})
})
.catch(error => {
console.log('Error fetching and parsing data', error);
});
}
}

posts.title: SQL Table to JSON Converter
posts.post:
This app is part of a much larger application which I have yet to release/publish. However, project's name is exactly what it accomplishes.


I wanted to convert a SQLite database file to a format which is easy for JavaScript manipulation.


I've developed the app within Node.js, combining several packages which allow for the uploading, parsing, and conversion of SQL database files contianing multiple tables into a single JSON file.


This tool is developed to convert specific sets of data from the tables within the file and not for any SQL file without major modifications.


Below is a screenshot of one of the tables for input:



The code featured below is the core of the app itself:


const converter = () => {
    var sqlite3 = require('sqlite3'),
        SqliteToJson = require('sqlite-to-json'),
        initialConversion = require('./initial-conversion.js'),
        convertCategory = require('./convert-category.js'),
        convertAttribute = require('./convert-attribute.js'),
        convertType = require('./convert-type.js'),
        convertLevel = require('./convert-level.js'),
        tutorCheck = require('./tutor-check.js'),
        disruptionCheck = require('./disruption-check.js'),
        convertAtkDef = require('./convert-atk.js'),
        bossCheck = require('./boss-check.js'),
        normalSumCheck = require('./normal-summon-check.js'),
        oncePerTurnCheck = require('./opt-check.js'),
        drawPowerCheck = require('./draw-power-check'),
        quickEffCheck = require('./quick-effect-check.js'),
        costCheck = require('./cost-checker.js'),
        advCheck = require('./advantage-check.js'),
        cardData = require('./card-data'),
        checkForbidden = require('./check-forbidden-list.js'),
        exportCards = require('./export-data.js'),
        exporter = new SqliteToJson({
        client: new sqlite3.Database('./database-converter/input/cards.cdb'),
    });
    // The Exporter selects all tables and returns its column and cell values as separate arrays within an object
    const exportData = exporter.all((err, all) => {
        // The rawData variable stores both all tables as separate arrays
        // The cardData variable stores the datas table
        // The cardText variable stores the texts table
        let originalData = [];
        const customData = [];
        originalData = initialConversion(all);
        // Now we want to store the cards in a human readable object which also includes deck-optimizer friendly variables
        for (let i = 0; i < originalData.length; i++) {
            const card = originalData[i];
            let newCard = cardData(card);
            // Monster categroy conversion
            convertCategory(newCard, card);
            // Monster attribute conversion
            convertAttribute(newCard, card);
            // Monster type conversion
            convertType(newCard, card);
            // Monster Level Conversion
            convertLevel(newCard, card);
            // Convert attack and defense values
            convertAtkDef(newCard, card);
            // Determine if boss monster
            bossCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine if monster can be normal summoned
            normalSumCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine if card has a quick-effect
            quickEffCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine if card is disruptive
            disruptionCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine if card has once per turn clause
            oncePerTurnCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine if the card tutors other cards
            tutorCheck(newCard, card);
            // If the query matches any monster type
            //Determine if the card provides draw power
            drawPowerCheck(newCard, card);
            //Determine card costs
            costCheck(newCard, card);
            // Determine card advantages
            advCheck(newCard, card);
            // Check if card is on forbidden and limited list
            checkForbidden(newCard, card);


            // Calculate total net card advantage for each card
            newCard.net = newCard.cost + newCard.adv;
            //Push new card into custom data array
            customData.push(newCard);
        }
        exportCards(customData);
    });
}


module.exports = converter;


Here is a sample of the output:

posts.title: Student Directory
posts.post:
The student directory project required separating large ordered lists into a pagination display, allowing end users to navigate through each page of students.


// Split the array of students into groups of ten
grouper = (array) => {
    let groups = [],
    group = [];
    // We want to push 10 students into the group array
    for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
        group.push(array[i])
        // When the group array length is equal to ten, we want to push it to the groups array and start over
        if(group.length === 10) {
            groups.push(group);
            group = [];
        }
    }
    // Whatever remains in the group array shall get pushed into the groups array and return the array
    groups.push(group);
    return groups;
},


Additionally, a search bar at the top of the page allows for the filtering out students by name. An error message is displayed if the query returns no results. 


search = () => {
    // We'll need to grab the names of each of the students and store them in a format comparable with a query
    const studentNames = document.querySelectorAll('.student-details > h3'),
        query = searchBar.value.toLowerCase();
    let results = [],
        studentArrays;

    for (let i = 0; i < students.length; i++) {
        let studentName = studentNames[i].textContent;
        if (studentName.indexOf(query) > -1) {
            results.push(students[i]);
        }
    }
    studentArrays = grouper(results)
    filterStudents(studentArrays);
}
